00:28:32.550 --> 00:28:33.630
it turned out.

00:28:33.630 --> 00:28:36.610
So, I chose this particular
image because to me

00:28:36.610 --> 00:28:39.254
it's the most important one ever recorded.

00:28:39.254 --> 00:28:42.210
It has two different
atoms, gallium and arsenic.

00:28:42.210 --> 00:28:43.530
You don't have to know anything about them

00:28:43.530 --> 00:28:46.930
other than that arsenic likes
electrons more than gallium.

00:28:46.930 --> 00:28:49.960
And so all the electrons
that are involved in bonding

00:28:49.960 --> 00:28:51.560
sit on the arsenic,

00:28:51.560 --> 00:28:54.280
and all the orbitals on
the gallium are empty.

00:28:54.280 --> 00:28:56.750
And so with this microscope
we can send electrons

00:28:56.750 --> 00:28:58.410
into the empty orbitals,

00:28:58.410 --> 00:29:01.410
and take them out in two
different measurements

00:29:03.310 --> 00:29:05.490
of the filled orbitals,

00:29:05.490 --> 00:29:08.490
and really look at where the electrons are

00:29:08.490 --> 00:29:09.650
and where they aren't,

00:29:09.650 --> 00:29:11.640
kind of like no theater.

00:29:11.640 --> 00:29:16.120
And that turns out to be just
the way an atom or molecule

00:29:16.120 --> 00:29:18.890
cruising along the surface
would see that surface,

00:29:18.890 --> 00:29:22.320
and it lets us explore and
understand the chemistry

00:29:22.320 --> 00:29:24.260
with better than atomic resolution,

00:29:24.260 --> 00:29:27.030
as if we could put on goggles

00:29:27.030 --> 00:29:28.790
that show us the chemistry of a surface.

00:29:28.790 --> 00:29:32.930
So that led to many,
many other capabilities.

00:29:32.930 --> 00:29:34.680
One of the things I did when I was at IBM

00:29:34.680 --> 00:29:38.090
was I wanted to find out what
was underneath those atoms,

00:29:38.090 --> 00:29:40.490
so I rewrote the software on a microscope

00:29:40.490 --> 00:29:42.200
to slide them out of the way.

00:29:42.200 --> 00:29:44.815
I didn't spell anything,
that came after I left,

00:29:44.815 --> 00:29:47.560
but that let us position atoms

00:29:47.560 --> 00:29:50.140
and formed these precise structures,

00:29:50.140 --> 00:29:53.000
like this famous quantum corral image,

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:54.860
where I'll point out all these waves

00:29:54.860 --> 00:29:56.440
are not extra atoms.

00:29:56.440 --> 00:29:59.050
They're just the electrons
interfering with each other,

00:29:59.050 --> 00:30:01.660
as if we threw a rock in a calm pond.

00:30:01.660 --> 00:30:05.050
And so we now understand
the chemistry that results

00:30:05.050 --> 00:30:08.850
from having those extra electrons
right in the middle there.

00:30:08.850 --> 00:30:10.920
There will be a molecule
that would wanna sit

00:30:10.920 --> 00:30:12.930
at that one particular point,

00:30:12.930 --> 00:30:16.210
not because of any special
chemistry of what's underneath.

00:30:16.210 --> 00:30:18.005
Everything is the same, it's all copper,

00:30:18.005 --> 00:30:23.005
