think about where it came from,

00:45:16.280 --> 00:45:19.680
which was really the
Renaissance idea of space,

00:45:19.680 --> 00:45:22.930
and it's Brunelleschi who either discovers

00:45:22.930 --> 00:45:26.150
or rediscovers the idea of perspective,

00:45:26.150 --> 00:45:29.870
and in that it turns
out that of course space

00:45:29.870 --> 00:45:31.830
is a kind of mathematics,

00:45:31.830 --> 00:45:36.260
and that we can actually
develop a science of space

00:45:36.260 --> 00:45:39.070
through the process of its representation,

00:45:39.070 --> 00:45:42.660
and that the construction
of three dimensions

00:45:42.660 --> 00:45:43.810
into two dimensions,

00:45:43.810 --> 00:45:47.330
which you see so beautifully
rendered in this etching,

00:45:47.330 --> 00:45:49.500
actually helps in the construction

00:45:49.500 --> 00:45:54.500
of particularly spectacular
and innovative buildings,

00:45:54.580 --> 00:45:58.773
like the Duomo in Florence
that Brunelleschi himself made.

00:46:01.060 --> 00:46:02.543
During this period,

00:46:05.987 --> 00:46:07.680
Sigfried Giedion, who wrote the book

00:46:07.680 --> 00:46:11.390
Space, Time and Architecure in 1941,

00:46:11.390 --> 00:46:14.180
says that the ultimate example

00:46:14.180 --> 00:46:18.880
of Renaissance and perspectival space,

00:46:18.880 --> 00:46:21.040
is really the City of Paris,

00:46:21.040 --> 00:46:23.770
with Haussmann's and Napoleon III's help.

00:46:23.770 --> 00:46:26.530
And you see in this before and after image

00:46:26.530 --> 00:46:30.580
how the city becomes a
kind of outdoor room,

00:46:30.580 --> 00:46:34.890
a kind of space that you
would say is the city of form,

00:46:34.890 --> 00:46:38.920
according to the architect
and urbanist Albert Pope.

00:46:38.920 --> 00:46:41.160
And you can think about that city of form

00:46:41.160 --> 00:46:45.340
as being almost an excavation
through the mass of buildings,

00:46:45.340 --> 00:46:48.840
out of which streets or
piazzas of plazas are made.

00:46:48.840 --> 00:46:51.820
And so the city is almost a thick mat

00:46:51.820 --> 00:46:54.720
in which space can be discovered,

00:46:54.720 --> 00:46:56.500
or excavated.

00:46:56.500 --> 00:47:00.120
And in this reconstruction I
think it's important to note

00:47:00.120 --> 00:47:02.780
we often think of Haussmann and Paris

00:47:02.780 --> 00:47:04.760
as being its boulevards.

00:47:04.760 --> 00:47:08.250
But what makes the boulevard
is Haussmann's housing blocks,

00:47:08.250 --> 00:47:10.050
the apartment blocks that he made

00:47:10.050 --> 00:47:12.740
that became the urban filler in a way

00:47:12.740 --> 00:47:17.740
to lead you to the perspectival
object of your affection

00:47:18.240 --> 00:47:19.710
at the end of the vista,

00:47:19.710 --> 00:47:22.120
or at the end of the
