00:49:23.010 --> 00:49:25.990
So really the master
of modern architecture

00:49:25.990 --> 00:49:28.620
as anyone in the room who's
an architecture student

00:49:28.620 --> 00:49:30.890
would know is Le Corbusier,

00:49:30.890 --> 00:49:35.890
who writes in a book called
The Making of Modern Space.

00:49:36.220 --> 00:49:38.260
Let me make sure I have
that title correct.

00:49:38.260 --> 00:49:41.857
He writes, "A boundless depth opens up.

00:49:41.857 --> 00:49:46.656
"It faces the walls, drives
away contingent presences,

00:49:46.656 --> 00:49:50.890
"accomplishes the miracle
of ineffable space."

00:49:50.890 --> 00:49:52.940
And I think even in that language,

00:49:52.940 --> 00:49:56.500
Corbu was a beautiful
writer as well as architect.

00:49:56.500 --> 00:50:01.070
He portrays this notion of an abstraction

00:50:01.070 --> 00:50:05.110
that the architect then
was there to try to capture

00:50:05.950 --> 00:50:10.100
as this almost existential,
ineffable task,

00:50:11.440 --> 00:50:13.220
which the Ozanne Pond Studio I think

00:50:13.220 --> 00:50:15.700
is a perfect example of...

00:50:15.700 --> 00:50:18.003
This is in the book
The New World of Space.

00:50:25.100 --> 00:50:28.060
But Corbu thought that the major arts,

00:50:28.060 --> 00:50:31.824
which he defined as
architecture, sculpture,

00:50:31.824 --> 00:50:35.544
city planning, and painting or drawing,

00:50:35.544 --> 00:50:38.720
were in fact all united and major

00:50:38.720 --> 00:50:41.060
because they were all about space.

00:50:41.060 --> 00:50:44.270
And so you see in his Ville Radieuse,

00:50:44.270 --> 00:50:47.690
the city itself is a plane of space

00:50:47.690 --> 00:50:50.030
out of which architecture is situated.

00:50:50.030 --> 00:50:53.400
The Villa Savoye which is the example

00:50:53.400 --> 00:50:56.340
of spatial manipulation by the architect

00:50:56.340 --> 00:50:58.910
that he's freed the ground
plane by raising it up

00:50:58.910 --> 00:51:01.220
on columns or piloti,

00:51:01.220 --> 00:51:03.620
that he's freed the
facade by separating it

00:51:03.620 --> 00:51:04.600
from the structure,

00:51:04.600 --> 00:51:06.260
and that he's freed the barrier

00:51:06.260 --> 00:51:08.810
between the inside and outside
through the strip window

00:51:08.810 --> 00:51:11.000
that distributes light evenly throughout.

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:14.490
And that same freedom he
captures in that drawing

00:51:14.490 --> 00:51:17.500
which is left open, and though a boundary,

00:51:17.500 --> 00:51:19.093
is not at all bounded.

00:51:21.380 --> 00:51:23.830
So if you think about modern space

00:51:23.830 --> 00:51:26.150
as being the space of the city

00:51:26.150 --> 00:51:29.203
and now I'm gonna leap from
the building to the city,

00:51:30.270 --> 00:51:34.340
Los Angeles itself is part of the object

00:51:34.340 --> 00:51:37.950
of modernist urban spatial thinking.

00:51:37.950 --> 00:51:41.860
And Bunker Hill is probably
our best example of that,

00:51:41.860 --> 00:51:46.200
which in fact, in the
50s and 60s and the 70s

00:51:46.200 --> 00:51:48.090
was flattened and cleared,

00:51:48.090 --> 00:51:51.610
turned into a tabula
rasa, or a clean slate,

00:51:51.610 --> 00:51:55.230
so that the new modern abstract space

00:51:55.230 --> 00:51:56.950
could be built upon it.

00:51:56.950 --> 00:52:00.690
This is just one plan of many,
many plans that were made

00:52:00.690 --> 00:52:04.182
that would bring Los
Angeles into the modern era

00:52:04.182 --> 00:52:07.753
through its architectural composition.

00:52:08.970 --> 00:52:11.070
It's important to note even here though

00:52:11.070 --> 00:52:14.660
that the freeways are part
of what is constructing

00:52:14.660 --> 00:52:16.400
that space of the city.

00:52:16.400 --> 00:52:19.610
And probably the person who
brought that to our minds

00:52:19.610 --> 00:52:23.200
most clearly was the British
architectural historian

00:52:23.200 --> 00:52:25.270
Reyner Banham, who wrote the book:

00:52:25.270 --> 00:52:28.380
Los Angeles, Architecture
of Four Ecologies.

00:52:28.380 --> 00:52:30.590
And he thought that the freeways,

00:52:30.590 --> 00:52:32.570
of course he's writing in the late 60s,

00:52:32.570 --> 00:52:33.730
publishes it in the 70s

00:52:33.730 --> 00:52:35.770
when you could actually get
from one place to another

00:52:35.770 --> 00:52:36.603
on the freeway,

00:52:36.603 --> 00:52:37.436
(audience laughing)

00:52:37.436 --> 00:52:42.070
that he writes that that's
his whole space of existence.

00:52:42.070 --> 00:52:44.220
The freeway system in its totality

00:52:44.220 --> 00:52:47.380
is now a single comprehensible place,

00:52:47.380 --> 00:52:51.100
a coherent state of mind,
a complete way of life,

00:52:51.100 --> 00:52:52.900
the fourth ecology of the Angelino.

00:52:52.900 --> 00:52:55.020
And I bolden the place,

00:52:55.020 --> 00:52:57.630
because it's the way we have distinguished

00:52:57.630 --> 00:53:01.260
in most recent history,

00:53:01.260 --> 00:53:02.690
space from place,

00:53:02.690 --> 00:53:05.030
that somehow space is
something that exists

00:53:05.030 --> 00:53:08.070
and can be passed through
or extends abstractly

00:53:08.070 --> 00:53:11.333
from this world, place
is a site of dwelling.

00:53:12.220 --> 00:53:14.120
And he was making the point

00:53:14.120 --> 00:53:17.540
that in fact the freeways
were a site of dwelling.

00:53:17.540 --> 00:53:21.070
What he didn't acknowledge
is that the freeways

00:53:21.070 --> 00:53:24.420
wiped out dwellings everywhere they went,

00:53:24.420 --> 00:53:26.810
and that that was their national task.

00:53:26.810 --> 00:53:30.680
And in fact we can see that
the Boyle Heights neighborhood

00:53:30.680 --> 00:53:32.800
has been particularly victimized

00:53:32.800 --> 00:53:35.020
both by the East L.A. interchange,

00:53:35.020 --> 00:53:37.300
but also by the 101,

00:53:37.300 --> 00:53:41.380
as a means of eradicating
poor neighborhoods of color.

00:53:41.380 --> 00:53:45.350
And so the politics of space
really starts to play into

00:53:45.350 --> 00:53:49.494
this next era of both transformation,

00:53:49.494 --> 00:53:54.410
and of what we'll later call reclamation.

