00:58:26.330 --> 00:58:28.743
It's also, in astronomy,

00:58:29.810 --> 00:58:32.610
actually astronomy's one
of the oldest sciences

00:58:32.610 --> 00:58:35.893
because we have an amazing
ability to study space.

00:58:36.960 --> 00:58:38.700
With just your eye,

00:58:38.700 --> 00:58:40.360
which of course is one of our,

00:58:40.360 --> 00:58:42.450
gives us one of our five senses,

00:58:42.450 --> 00:58:46.820
we can see well beyond the
boundaries of our own galaxy

00:58:46.820 --> 00:58:48.750
to the next closest galaxy.

00:58:48.750 --> 00:58:52.330
And if you compare that to
any of our other senses,

00:58:52.330 --> 00:58:54.100
that's rather astounding,

00:58:54.100 --> 00:58:56.750
how far we can smell,

00:58:56.750 --> 00:58:58.180
how far we can taste,

00:58:58.180 --> 00:58:59.650
how far we can hear.

00:58:59.650 --> 00:59:02.580
But our ability of sight
really brings space

00:59:02.580 --> 00:59:05.650
that's very large to us.

00:59:05.650 --> 00:59:07.990
Now, people have been studying astronomy

00:59:07.990 --> 00:59:09.810
for a very long time.

00:59:09.810 --> 00:59:13.390
But today, the study of astronomical space

00:59:13.390 --> 00:59:16.050
as is carried out with
very large telescopes.

00:59:16.050 --> 00:59:17.690
So I have to share with you

00:59:17.690 --> 00:59:21.338
one of the wonderful
aspects of being at UCLA

00:59:21.338 --> 00:59:26.260
is that UC owns the largest
telescopes in the world.

00:59:26.260 --> 00:59:28.563
These are co-owned by UC and Caltech.

00:59:29.670 --> 00:59:32.270
They're not in a bad space here on Earth.

00:59:32.270 --> 00:59:33.730
They're out in Hawaii,

00:59:33.730 --> 00:59:37.220
so most of the folks here at UCLA

00:59:37.220 --> 00:59:40.450
carry our their work
with these telescopes.

00:59:40.450 --> 00:59:42.380
So it used to be that we
had to go up to the summit,

00:59:42.380 --> 00:59:44.660
but in fact now you can
control these facilities

00:59:44.660 --> 00:59:47.370
here from UCLA.

00:59:47.370 --> 00:59:51.320
Now, telescopes allow us to see very far.

00:59:51.320 --> 00:59:52.500
The bigger the telescope,

00:59:52.500 --> 00:59:53.800
the larger the collecting area

00:59:53.800 --> 00:59:56.560
so you can see things that are faint.

00:59:56.560 --> 00:59:57.500
And in astronomy,

00:59:57.500 --> 00:59:59.560
faint corresponds to
things that are far away.

00:59:59.560 --> 01:00:02.370
So that's one aspect of distance.

01:00:02.370 --> 01:00:04.180
Another aspect of distance,

01:00:04.180 --> 01:00:06.630
because space we usually
think of as three dimensions,

01:00:06.630 --> 01:00:08.410
but of course, if you're a
physicist, you might think:

01:00:08.410 --> 01:00:10.800
well maybe not, maybe
it's nine, 10, or 11,

01:00:10.800 --> 01:00:12.240
and we can debate about that,

01:00:12.240 --> 01:00:15.480
but we're gonna today stick
to three dimensions of space

01:00:15.480 --> 01:00:16.990
and one dimension of time.

01:00:16.990 --> 01:00:20.460
So my thinking about
space is four dimensional.

01:00:20.460 --> 01:00:21.683
So we have distance,

01:00:22.550 --> 01:00:24.320
which is our distance away from us,

01:00:24.320 --> 01:00:26.140
and then in a plane of the sky,

01:00:26.140 --> 01:00:27.800
what we see out in the universe,

01:00:27.800 --> 01:00:29.320
there's two dimensions of space,

01:00:29.320 --> 01:00:30.570
and then of course there's time.

01:00:30.570 --> 01:00:32.220
So we're gonna come back to time.

01:00:33.530 --> 01:00:37.217
Now, this is the humbling part.

01:00:37.217 --> 01:00:38.813
(laughs)

01:00:38.813 --> 01:00:42.460
It used to be we thought we
were the center here on Earth.

01:00:42.460 --> 01:00:44.120
We thought space surrounded us

01:00:44.120 --> 01:00:46.970
and that we were at
the epicenter of space.

01:00:46.970 --> 01:00:48.530
But of course, with Galileo,

01:00:48.530 --> 01:00:52.260
Galileo who was committed to house arrest

01:00:52.260 --> 01:00:55.300
for this radical notion that we were not

01:00:55.300 --> 01:00:56.800
at the center of everything,

01:00:56.800 --> 01:01:00.140
we now recognize that the Earth
is just one of many planets

01:01:00.140 --> 01:01:01.750
that orbit the sun,

01:01:01.750 --> 01:01:04.540
which in fact is quite ordinary.
So in fact we had a phase

01:01:04.540 --> 01:01:06.360
where we thought the sun was special.

01:01:06.360 --> 01:01:08.370
But now we realize not even the sun

01:01:08.370 --> 01:01:10.500
that we orbit is special.

01:01:10.500 --> 01:01:13.080
Our galaxy is composed of roughly

01:01:13.080 --> 01:01:16.210
100 billion stars like the sun.

01:01:16.210 --> 01:01:20.112
The sun you can think
of as a middle age star,

01:01:20.112 --> 01:01:23.011
ready to go out and get
that red sports car.

01:01:23.011 --> 01:01:23.844
(audience laughing)

01:01:23.844 --> 01:01:25.240
It's five billion years old.

01:01:25.240 --> 01:01:27.260
It's halfway through its lifetime,

01:01:27.260 --> 01:01:31.210
which is also another humbling
thought in terms of space.

01:01:31.210 --> 01:01:34.740
Our sun, when it runs
out of gas, and it will,

01:01:34.740 --> 01:01:36.530
in another five billion years,

01:01:36.530 --> 01:01:37.810
is going to expand.

01:01:37.810 --> 01:01:39.680
So we live in a dynamic universe,

01:01:39.680 --> 01:01:43.870
and it will expand to envelop the Earth.

01:01:43.870 --> 01:01:47.120
So if you ever forget what
order the planets come in

01:01:47.120 --> 01:01:49.440
just remember the TV show
Third Rock From The Sun,

01:01:49.440 --> 01:01:52.653
or Third Rock, because we are
the third rock from the sun.

01:01:53.630 --> 01:01:55.860
So at some point the sun
will actually envelop us,

01:01:55.860 --> 01:01:57.710
which actually I think really drives us

01:01:57.710 --> 01:01:59.780
to think about exploring space.

01:01:59.780 --> 01:02:02.990
Can we get off this rock and go further?

01:02:02.990 --> 01:02:04.500
Because there will be a moment,

01:02:04.500 --> 01:02:06.380
if we manage to survive,

01:02:06.380 --> 01:02:09.510
where we will need to
explore the larger universe

01:02:10.430 --> 01:02:11.263
by moving.

01:02:12.480 --> 01:02:14.590
All right, so in our
universe, we not only,

01:02:14.590 --> 01:02:16.630
we have the sun, and
we said that there's...

01:02:16.630 --> 01:02:18.000
The sun is pretty typical,

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:20.610
and now we have the
ability to recognize that

01:02:23.370 --> 01:02:26.060
the stage that the sun
is in is pretty boring,

01:02:26.060 --> 01:02:29.120
actually it's pretty
static, fortunately for us.

01:02:29.120 --> 01:02:32.090
But there are some really
interesting and dynamic parts

01:02:32.090 --> 01:02:34.600
of a star's life.

01:02:34.600 --> 01:02:36.080
Just like a human's life,

01:02:36.080 --> 01:02:37.860
the most exciting parts tend to be

01:02:37.860 --> 01:02:39.730
the beginning and the end.

01:02:39.730 --> 01:02:40.563
So in the beginning,

01:02:40.563 --> 01:02:43.220
this is a picture that shows
the beginning of stars' lives.

01:02:43.220 --> 01:02:45.850
And if you go further with this analogy

01:02:45.850 --> 01:02:48.040
with a human lifetime,

01:02:48.040 --> 01:02:49.580
the birth of a star

01:02:49.580 --> 01:02:53.250
compared to the age of
a typical star's life

01:02:53.250 --> 01:02:55.450
is like a human gestation period.

01:02:55.450 --> 01:02:58.480
So on stars' timescales,

01:02:58.480 --> 01:03:02.070
this is a few million years of time passes

01:03:02.070 --> 01:03:04.600
as the star goes through
the process of collapsing

01:03:04.600 --> 01:03:07.100
from enormous scales,

01:03:07.100 --> 01:03:09.873
down to the size of our
sun and our solar system.

01:03:10.710 --> 01:03:11.890
So this is the beginning.

01:03:11.890 --> 01:03:15.990
Now, just like humans,
the end is also exciting.

01:03:15.990 --> 01:03:18.679
We already alluded to the end of the sun,

01:03:18.679 --> 01:03:22.410
but in fact our sun is
a fairly small star,

01:03:22.410 --> 01:03:25.540
and it ends its life...

01:03:25.540 --> 01:03:27.280
Well, while we say it's gonna be dramatic

01:03:27.280 --> 01:03:29.460
because it's gonna envelop the Earth,

01:03:29.460 --> 01:03:32.620
in an astronomical sense it's
actually rather non-dramatic.

01:03:32.620 --> 01:03:35.830
The massive stars are
the ones that explode.

01:03:35.830 --> 01:03:38.470
This is a picture of an exploding star.

01:03:38.470 --> 01:03:40.380
So we have a dynamic
(mumbles) nervous again

01:03:40.380 --> 01:03:42.230
because if we go from
things at the beginning

01:03:42.230 --> 01:03:45.210
that are shrinking to at the
end where things are expanding,

01:03:45.210 --> 01:03:47.100
and expanding quite explosively.

01:03:47.100 --> 01:03:49.090
And in this explosion,

01:03:49.090 --> 01:03:51.470
it's actually where we get
the chemical complexity

01:03:51.470 --> 01:03:54.270
that we so appreciate here on Earth.

01:03:54.270 --> 01:03:58.940
Our universe starts off
with incredible simplicity.

01:03:58.940 --> 01:04:00.740
It's just hydrogen.

01:04:00.740 --> 01:04:03.070
And out of the inner workings of stars

01:04:03.070 --> 01:04:06.220
we can build up to more
chemical complexity,

01:04:06.220 --> 01:04:10.880
up to iron, but in fact iron
is a pretty simple atom.

01:04:10.880 --> 01:04:14.410
And it's only in these
exploding massive stars

01:04:14.410 --> 01:04:17.570
that we get all the complexity
that we so appreciate here,

01:04:17.570 --> 01:04:20.620
like gold, or anything
that your cellphones

01:04:20.620 --> 01:04:23.320
are created from,

01:04:23.320 --> 01:04:26.773
are created in these
explosions of massive stars.

01:04:28.388 --> 01:04:31.280
Now we've gone from a point where we said

01:04:31.280 --> 01:04:33.990
the Earth was the middle, to
the sun that was the middle.

01:04:33.990 --> 01:04:36.430
And then a mere hundred years ago,

01:04:36.430 --> 01:04:38.510
and to me this is rather amazing,

01:04:38.510 --> 01:04:42.322
100 years ago we thought
our own galaxy was it.

01:04:42.322 --> 01:04:43.155
(laughing)

01:04:43.155 --> 01:04:46.600
And today, we recognize that our galaxy,

01:04:46.600 --> 01:04:49.080
and if we could get outside
our own galaxy and look back,

01:04:49.080 --> 01:04:50.950
this is what our galaxy would look like.

01:04:50.950 --> 01:04:52.923
We live about halfway out.

01:04:54.090 --> 01:04:56.170
It's just one of many, many, many,

01:04:56.170 --> 01:04:59.109
billions and billions of galaxies,

01:04:59.109 --> 01:04:59.942
(laughing)

01:04:59.942 --> 01:05:01.890
as many others have said.

01:05:01.890 --> 01:05:03.920
The galaxy that I was just
showing you a moment ago

01:05:03.920 --> 01:05:06.020
is the one in the top left.

01:05:06.020 --> 01:05:09.380
So today we understand that in fact

01:05:09.380 --> 01:05:12.900
there's a universe that's on
a much, much larger scale.

01:05:12.900 --> 01:05:16.800
So in the last mere hundred
years of our history

01:05:16.800 --> 01:05:21.060
we've come to understand the
vastness of the universe.

01:05:21.060 --> 01:05:23.829
Now, (laughs)

01:05:23.829 --> 01:05:25.130
(audience laughing)

01:05:25.130 --> 01:05:28.600
we collect this information
primarily through telescopes.

01:05:28.600 --> 01:05:32.130
We're collecting light, or photons,

01:05:32.130 --> 01:05:33.430
which are little light packets.

01:05:33.430 --> 01:05:35.800
And it turns out that these light packets,

01:05:35.800 --> 01:05:37.590
these carriers of information,

01:05:37.590 --> 01:05:40.560
do not travel at infinite speed,

01:05:40.560 --> 01:05:43.180
but they travel at the speed of light,

01:05:43.180 --> 01:05:45.990
which we actually think of
as the cosmic speed limit.

01:05:45.990 --> 01:05:47.609
Nothing can go faster in our universe

01:05:47.609 --> 01:05:49.690
than the speed of light.

01:05:49.690 --> 01:05:52.870
But this means that as
we study the universe,

01:05:52.870 --> 01:05:57.700
we're not seeing it as it is today,

01:05:57.700 --> 01:06:00.710
but rather as it is when that photon

01:06:00.710 --> 01:06:03.630
that you're collecting
was emitted from it.

01:06:03.630 --> 01:06:08.630
And because we are now studying
scales that are so big,

01:06:08.830 --> 01:06:11.740
what we're really getting
is a history lesson.

01:06:11.740 --> 01:06:14.600
And to give you a sense of this,

01:06:14.600 --> 01:06:15.930
I study the center of the galaxy.

01:06:15.930 --> 01:06:18.570
That's my favorite place
in the universe to look at.

01:06:18.570 --> 01:06:23.440
The light from the center of
the galaxy takes 26,000 years

01:06:23.440 --> 01:06:27.910
to get from the center of
the galaxy to our telescopes.

01:06:27.910 --> 01:06:29.790
So I have to say I'm very excited

01:06:29.790 --> 01:06:32.479
about an event that's happening,

01:06:32.479 --> 01:06:36.333
just culminating now
over the last six months.

01:06:37.180 --> 01:06:40.830
But that six months
happened 26,000 years ago.

01:06:40.830 --> 01:06:44.730
Okay, so that's already
mind blowing to me.

01:06:44.730 --> 01:06:47.980
But that's nothing in astrophysics.

01:06:47.980 --> 01:06:51.840
So once we get going to
the next closest galaxy,

01:06:51.840 --> 01:06:53.840
we're talking two million years ago.

01:06:53.840 --> 01:06:56.160
That's the light that we're collecting.

01:06:56.160 --> 01:06:59.810
And when we talk about
the edge of the universe

01:06:59.810 --> 01:07:01.720
that we can see today,

