So in fact we're not seeing
these places in space (laughs)

01:07:10.110 --> 01:07:14.190
as they are today, but
as they were so long ago.

01:07:14.190 --> 01:07:16.430
So that's one way in which space

01:07:16.430 --> 01:07:18.863
is highly connected to time.

01:07:20.250 --> 01:07:23.570
Now there's another way in which
space is connected to time,

01:07:23.570 --> 01:07:25.860
and that's if you get near objects

01:07:25.860 --> 01:07:27.980
that have large gravitational fields.

01:07:27.980 --> 01:07:29.960
My favorite subjects in
the universe to study

01:07:29.960 --> 01:07:30.960
are black holes.

01:07:30.960 --> 01:07:32.500
Turns out there's a
super massive black hole

01:07:32.500 --> 01:07:33.840
at the center of the galaxy (laughs)

01:07:33.840 --> 01:07:36.900
or a million (laughs)
times the mass of the sun,

01:07:36.900 --> 01:07:40.490
crammed into a space the
size of our solar system.

01:07:40.490 --> 01:07:42.124
So, lots of mass, small space,

01:07:42.124 --> 01:07:44.110
that's the proof of a black hole.

01:07:44.110 --> 01:07:45.860
But why do we care about it in the context

01:07:45.860 --> 01:07:47.360
of this discussion?

01:07:47.360 --> 01:07:50.100
We care about it in the
context of this discussion

01:07:50.100 --> 01:07:52.590
because when you get near black holes

01:07:52.590 --> 01:07:55.750
or any object that has
a gravitational field,

01:07:55.750 --> 01:07:58.900
you get this mixing of space and time.

01:07:58.900 --> 01:08:01.470
So if you go to any science museum,

01:08:01.470 --> 01:08:03.170
there's the classic gravity well,

01:08:04.150 --> 01:08:06.650
and that's supposed to
represent the concept

01:08:06.650 --> 01:08:09.760
of two dimensions of space being mixed.

01:08:09.760 --> 01:08:11.580
They flatten that one dimension of space

01:08:11.580 --> 01:08:13.250
with one dimension of time.

01:08:13.250 --> 01:08:15.030
So, if you were to send your buddy,

01:08:15.030 --> 01:08:16.430
or maybe not so much your buddy,

01:08:16.430 --> 01:08:17.360
into the black hole,

01:08:17.360 --> 01:08:19.000
(audience laughing)

01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:24.000
you would see your buddy
get slower and slower

01:08:24.650 --> 01:08:28.600
and then pause at a magic
distance from the black hole

01:08:28.600 --> 01:08:29.660
known as the event horizon.

01:08:29.660 --> 01:08:30.800
They'd just stop.

01:08:30.800 --> 01:08:33.630
And that's because it's
very hard for the photon

01:08:33.630 --> 01:08:35.700
that's the carrier of
information to make it

01:08:35.700 --> 01:08:37.250
from them to us.

01:08:37.250 --> 01:08:38.940
It's the mixing of space-time.

01:08:38.940 --> 01:08:43.530
Your buddy, his experience,
or her experience,

01:08:43.530 --> 01:08:45.220
would be to get faster and faster

01:08:45.220 --> 01:08:47.320
and go right through the event horizon.

01:08:47.320 --> 01:08:49.310
So that is an aspect of space

01:08:49.310 --> 01:08:52.403
that I find particularly fascinating.

01:08:54.634 --> 01:08:57.142
I'm just gonna skip over these things.

01:08:57.142 --> 01:09:02.142
Just to share that our ability
to study space and time

01:09:02.640 --> 01:09:06.130
is advanced by having larger
and larger telescopes.

01:09:06.130 --> 01:09:08.140
So UC has had the largest
telescope in the world

01:09:08.140 --> 01:09:09.250
for 100 years.

01:09:09.250 --> 01:09:12.135
The Keck telescope is just
the latest and greatest.

01:09:12.135 --> 01:09:14.100
It's been around for 25 years.

01:09:14.100 --> 01:09:15.980
But we're in the middle of building

01:09:15.980 --> 01:09:18.610
an even bigger telescope.

01:09:18.610 --> 01:09:20.833
